The '''black-thighed grosbeak''' ('''''Pheucticus tibialis''''') is a large [[seed]]-eating [[bird]] in the family [[Cardinalidae]], which is endemic to the mountains of [[Costa Rica]] and western [[Panama]].

This species breeds from about {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} altitude ([[Pacific]] slope) or {{convert|1500|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Caribbean]] slope) up to {{convert|2600|m|ft|abbr=on}} and is found in canopy, woodland edge and semi-open habitats such as pasture with some trees. The nest is a thin [[cup nest|cup]] constructed on a bulky twig base {{convert|1|–|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} up in a small tree or amongst vines. The female lays two brown-spotted pale blue eggs between March and May.

The adult black-thighed grosbeak is {{convert|20|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, weighs {{convert|70|g|oz|abbr=on}}, and has a massive grey bill. The male has a yellow head, rump and underparts, an olive-edged black back, and black wings, thighs and tail. There is a white patch on the flight feathers. The female is paler with more olive on the back and a smaller white wing patch. Immatures are duller and more olive-tinged, and have streaking and mottling on the body plumage.

The black-thighed grosbeak forages in shrubs or trees for [[insect]]s, seeds and [[Berry|berries]]. The call is a sharp ''pink'', and the song is a musical stream of warbles, whistles, trills and slurs.

